    <title>Combined summary - Adding New BIP Editors</title>
    <updated>2024-04-02T02:06:54.751730+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://gnusha.org/pi/bitcoindev/CAMHHROw9mZJRnTbUo76PdqwJU==YJMvd9Qrst+nmyypaedYZgg@mail.gmail.com/T/#m7e0fd600bbebb3a618c735f1958eca5214e90278" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The discussions on enhancing the Bitcoin Improvement Proposal (BIP) process emphasize a multifaceted approach to selecting new BIP editors, underlining the significance of transparency, inclusivity, and a structured yet flexible methodology. The role of BIP editors is crucial, involving not only the technical evaluation of proposals but also administrative tasks such as assigning BIP numbers, potentially influencing the improvement trajectory of Bitcoin. Concerns about editorial control, including potential censorship and the assignment process for BIP numbers, highlight the need for clear protocols and expectations for these positions.

Candidates for the BIP editor role, including Bryan "Kanzure" Bishop, Ruben Somsen, Jon Atack, Olaoluwa "Roasbeef" Osuntokun, Mark "Murch" Erhardt, and Michael Folkson, have been identified based on community recommendations. Their qualifications are assessed in light of their contributions to discussions, drafting of BIPs, and familiarity with the process, with Murch noted for his extensive contributions and suitability for the role.

The dialogue extends to broader issues within the BIP process, advocating for principles like least privilege, the value of multilingual editors, and strategies for deprecating outdated standards. A proposed “fast-track” number assignment system aims to streamline proposal tracking, suggesting a collective readiness to address bureaucratic challenges and enhance efficiency. Moreover, the need for transparent guidance for BIP editors is stressed, proposing a more open contrast to how Core maintainers typically operate.

Further discussions propose an alternative approach to BIP numbering using a bot for initial assignments, with permanent numbers given upon merge, aimed at simplifying the lifecycle management of BIPs. This part of the conversation underscores the importance of moving forward without delay in appointing new editors armed with full privileges as outlined in [BIP 2](https://github.com/bitcoin/bips/blob/master/bip-0002.mediawikiuser-content-BIP_Editor_Responsibilities__Workflow).

A shift towards democratizing the assessment of technical soundness of proposals is considered, suggesting a wider engagement from the community in evaluating proposals. This reflects a collective effort in maintaining a high standard of review while ensuring the process remains inclusive and efficient.

The discussions also touch upon the practical aspects of BIP management, such as delays in proposal number assignments and the idea of involving non-developer triagers to resolve bottlenecks. This indicates a proactive approach to improving the organizational structure of BIP management and highlights the ongoing endeavor to refine the process for the betterment of Bitcoin's infrastructure, emphasizing innovation, decentralization, and open participation.</summary>
